<b>UNIX and Linux</b>
</big><br>

<p>

Tools:
<ul>
<li> From your Linux account, you can access manual pages for most commands 
and functions with the <tt>man</tt> command, e.g.
<pre>
    man getpid
</pre>
will tell you about the <tt>getpid( )</tt> system call.
For an alternative interface, check out <tt>xman</tt>.
<p>
If you don't know what the command is, 
<tt>man -k</tt>
lets you look up manpages by keyword.  
In the response, the numbers in parens indicate section
numbers; use <tt>man -S</tt> to specify section.
<li> Life is much easier if you use an editor that recognizes
your syntax, and highlights and indents appropriately. 
<p>
I like 
<tt>emacs</tt>.  (There are various X-enhanced versions around.)
But your mileage may vary.
</ul>
<p>
 Dartmouth CS has an <a href="http://www.cs.dartmouth.edu/unix/"><b>introduction to Unix</b></a> 
site.
<p>
 ATT had an interesting site on the 
<a href="http://www.bell-labs.com/history/unix/">
<b>history of Unix.</b></a>  (But the whole site is down right now...)
Another source:
 <a href="http://www.princeton.edu/~mike/unixhistory"><b>an oral history
of UNIX</b></a>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<a href="http://palantir.swarthmore.edu/maxwell/classes/tutorials/maketutor/"><b>Here</b></a>
is a useful site on makefiles.
<p>
<hr>

<p>
Bovet and Cesati's book (above)
is a good introduction
to the internal structure of Linux.
<p>
Stevens
is a good desktop reference for heavy-duty systems programming.
<p>
Here is a site with
<a href="http://lxr.linux.no/source/"><b>browsable Linux source</b></a>.
If you want to know which one to look up...
you can use <tt>uname -a</tt> to figure out the version and architecture
running on a particular machine.

<hr>
<p> 
 
<big><IMG ALIGN="bottom" SRC="http://www.cs.dartmouth.edu/images/greenball.gif" ALT="">  

<b>GNU Tools</b>
</big><br>
<p>

<cite>Programming with GNU Software</cite> (above)
is a good reference book, with a chapter
on each of the major tools: <tt>gcc</tt>, <tt>gdb</tt>, etc.
<p>

On-line resources:
<ul>
<li> <a href="http://gcc.gnu.org/onlinedocs/gcc-4.0.3/gcc/"><b>gcc</b></a>
<li> <a href="http://sources.redhat.com/gdb/current/onlinedocs/gdb.html"><b>gdb</b></a>
<li> <a href="http://www.gnu.org/software/make/manual/make.html"><b>make</b></a>
<li> <a href="http://www.gnu.org/software/libc/manual/"><b>glibc</b></a>
</ul>
<p>
(See also
<a href="http://www.cs.dartmouth.edu/~dwagn/cs58/tutorial/"><b>Dave Wagner's
C/GDB tutorial</b></a>)

<hr>
<p> 
 
<big><IMG ALIGN="bottom" SRC="http://www.cs.dartmouth.edu/images/greenball.gif" ALT="">  

<b>Threads</b>
</big><br>
<p>

<cite>Pthreads Programming</cite> (above)
is an excellent guide to 
to the POSIX threads package.
<p>

<a name="birrell">Andrew Birrell's</a>
<cite>"An Introduction to Programming with
  Threads"</cite> is a classic paper full of much good wisdom.
<A HREF="/~cs58/resources/SRC-035.pdf"><b>pdf</b></A>

<hr>
<p> 
 
<big><IMG ALIGN="bottom" SRC="http://www.cs.dartmouth.edu/images/greenball.gif" ALT="">  

<b>Security</b>
</big><br>

<p>
A nice (and free) guide to cryptography:
<a name="rsafaq">
RSA Laboratories.
<cite>Frequently Asked Questions about Today's Cryptography.</cite>
Version 4.1. May 2000.  
<a href="/~cs58/resources/rsalabs_faq41.pdf"><b>(pdf---with internal links)</b></a>
</a>
<p>
<a href="http://catless.ncl.ac.uk/Risks/"><b>The Risks Digest</b></a>
<p>  
<a href="http://www.securityfocus.com/"><b>SecurityFocus</b></a>
(where BugTraq comes from)
<p>
<a href="http://www.cert.org/"><b>CERT</b></a>
(US gov't-funded security response center at CMU)
<p>
<a href="http://www.cs.dartmouth.edu/~sws/wazzu/"><b>my wazzu collection</b></a>

